hidden camera,
[INAUDIBLE], family show.

00:25:45.150 --> 00:25:47.652
It's kind of a similar
point where you left off.

00:25:47.652 --> 00:25:49.360
It's on a couple of
shows here, you know,

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:50.895
that will recognize
and [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:50.895 --> 00:25:53.080
is kind of an extension
strategy, I guess.

00:25:53.080 --> 00:25:54.604
Do you think it's
the end for them?

00:25:54.604 --> 00:25:56.520
DOM JOLY: See, I should
never slag off comedy,

00:25:56.520 --> 00:25:57.228
but I'm going to.

00:25:57.228 --> 00:25:57.980
I hate that show.

00:25:57.980 --> 00:25:59.550
And I'll tell you why I hate it.

00:25:59.550 --> 00:26:02.360
I started off, the first job I
got on "The Mark Thomas Comedy

00:26:02.360 --> 00:26:05.100
Product," which was basically an
English version of the "Michael

00:26:05.100 --> 00:26:06.740
Moore Show" before
Michael Moore.

00:26:06.740 --> 00:26:08.762
And Mark is a stand
up who you might know.

00:26:08.762 --> 00:26:10.220
He's a bit of a
political activist.

00:26:10.220 --> 00:26:11.969
And he can get a bit
annoying occasionally

00:26:11.969 --> 00:26:13.880
with his militant setting.

00:26:13.880 --> 00:26:15.410
But the idea at
the time was good.

00:26:15.410 --> 00:26:19.632
It was like, let's take on MPs
and set them up and do stunts.

00:26:19.632 --> 00:26:21.090
And I think that
was the first one.

00:26:21.090 --> 00:26:22.620
And I was the
research on that show,

00:26:22.620 --> 00:26:23.920
and that's where I started off.

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:26.580
And then when I was doing early
stuff for "Trigger Happy,"

00:26:26.580 --> 00:26:29.330
I took that on. and I was
attacking Cool Britannia

00:26:29.330 --> 00:26:31.590
and putting fake
Millennium Domes

00:26:31.590 --> 00:26:33.667
in Peter Mandelson's
garden and standing

00:26:33.667 --> 00:26:34.750
as a teddy bear and stuff.

00:26:34.750 --> 00:26:37.610
And it was kind of
odd surreal activism.

00:26:37.610 --> 00:26:40.380
And when we went to Channel
4 to pitch for the show,

00:26:40.380 --> 00:26:42.070
I was actually
pitching show which

00:26:42.070 --> 00:26:43.744
was about taking
on Cool Britannia,

00:26:43.744 --> 00:26:45.410
and it was kind of a
bit like that show.

00:26:45.410 --> 00:26:47.140
And the commissioning
editor had just

00:26:47.140 --> 00:26:49.530
finished doing Chris
Morris's "Brass Eye," which

00:26:49.530 --> 00:26:52.586
literally she'd been in nothing
but legal battles for a year.

00:26:52.586 --> 00:26:54.460
And she just went, ah,
fuck, not another one.

00:26:54.460 --> 00:26:55.490
She said, please.

00:26:55.490 --> 00:26:58.064
If you can do anything
that wasn't socially based,

00:26:58.064 --> 00:26:59.730
so she said, can you
do something silly?

00:26:59.730 --> 00:27:01.460
And that's how "Trigger
Happy" happened.

00:27:01.460 --> 00:27:03.670
With "The Revolution
That Must Be Televised,"

00:27:03.670 --> 00:27:06.430
my problem with it,
genuinely, is that I just

00:27:06.430 --> 00:27:08.690
don't think it's that funny.

00:27:08.690 --> 00:27:11.660
And I think you either
have to do something

00:27:11.660 --> 00:27:14.172
where you're being funny,
and if you make a point,

00:27:14.172 --> 00:27:15.380
it's kind of as a side thing.

00:27:15.380 --> 00:27:18.800
Or you have to literally
be, I'm a hardcore whatever.

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:21.070
And I think they're
not that political,

00:27:21.070 --> 00:27:22.230
but they're not that funny.

00:27:22.230 --> 00:27:25.597
And so they end up
kind of just shoving

00:27:25.597 --> 00:27:26.680
microphones in their face.

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:28.810
But then maybe I'm just old and
I don't know comedy anymore.

00:27:28.810 --> 00:27:29.700
I don't know.

00:27:29.700 --> 00:27:31.485
I love the name of the show.

00:27:31.485 --> 00:27:32.860
And I kind of
think, yeah, you're

00:27:32.860 --> 00:27:35.735
exactly what I was, an annoying
little posh bloke 20 years ago.

00:27:35.735 --> 00:27:37.360
So probably that's
why I don't like it,

00:27:37.360 --> 00:27:38.901
because they're on
telly and I'm not.

00:27:38.901 --> 00:27:39.948
And they won a BAFTA.

00:27:39.948 --> 00:27:41.590
So did "Fonejacker."

00:27:41.590 --> 00:27:43.524
I didn't win a BAFTA,
so yeah, that's why.

00:27:43.524 --> 00:27:44.440
But good luck to them.

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:45.820
And the other thing
they do-- sorry--

00:27:45.820 --> 00:27:48.050
when they go to America,
what I've realized, again,

00:27:48.050 --> 00:27:49.383
is the classic way all shows go.

00:27:49.383 --> 00:27:50.940
You do two shows.

00:27:50.940 --> 00:27:53.200
Your second show's probably
a bit more successful.

00:27:53.200 --> 00:27:55.840
And then the third show, it's
called the "On the Buses"

00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:57.630
Spanish holiday thing.

00:27:57.630 --> 00:28:00.660
You suddenly think, fuck,
we can get people to come.

00:28:00.660 --> 00:28:03.030
So I started seeing if
I could get madness.

00:28:03.030 --> 00:28:04.154
You get cameos.

00:28:04.154 --> 00:28:06.820
And then once you've got all the
cameos of the people you want--

00:28:06.820 --> 00:28:09.866
so Ricky Gervais did it well
with "Extras"-- you then think,

00:28:09.866 --> 00:28:10.990
where can we go on holiday?

00:28:10.990 --> 00:28:12.820
We should go to do
an American show.

00:28:12.820 --> 00:28:15.348
And they very rarely
work when you go abroad.

00:28:15.348 --> 00:28:17.514
So I didn't answer anything
there, but there you go.

00:28:17.514 --> 00:28:18.382
AUDIENCE: No, no, no.

00:28:18.382 --> 00:28:18.816
It's good to hear
your opinion on it.

00:28:18.816 --> 00:28:19.250
Appreciate it.

00:28:19.250 --> 00:28:20.660
DOM JOLY: I'm really sorry
if you are watching this.

00:28:20.660 --> 00:28:21.730
I hate slagging off
other comedians.

00:28:21.730 --> 00:28:22.210
I'm not slagging him off.

00:28:22.210 --> 00:28:22.960
It's just whatever.

00:28:22.960 --> 00:28:24.928
AUDIENCE: Have you seen
much of YouTube videos,

00:28:24.928 --> 00:28:26.896
because prank videos are
quite big on YouTube,

00:28:26.896 --> 00:28:28.126
and I wonder if
you've seen them,

00:28:28.126 --> 00:28:30.792
or what "Trigger Happy" would've
been like if you'd done it now.

00:28:30.792 --> 00:28:33.920
DOM JOLY: Two things, really,
the reason "Trigger Happy"

00:28:33.920 --> 00:28:36.962
happened was because it
was just at that year

00:28:36.962 --> 00:28:39.720
where cameras became
available in the shops.

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:41.220
They were called
three chip cameras,

00:28:41.220 --> 00:28:43.350
which now when you look at
the quality, it's awful.

00:28:43.350 --> 00:28:45.600
But it was the first
time that for a grand

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:47.530
you could buy a
camera which you could

00:28:47.530 --> 00:28:50.970
use which was, at the time,
good enough to go on telly.

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:53.460
A year before that, if you
wanted to film anything,

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:56.590
you had to hire a proper
cameramen, proper sound man.

00:28:56.590 --> 00:28:58.510
Nothing wrong with that,
but they cost money.

00:28:58.510 --> 00:29:00.670
So it meant you only had
a limited amount of time.

00:29:00.670 --> 00:29:02.282
And suddenly we
bought that camera,

00:29:02.282 --> 00:29:03.990
and we just filmed
and filmed, because it

00:29:03.990 --> 00:29:05.390
wasn't costing any money.

00:29:05.390 --> 00:29:06.570
So that was huge.

00:29:06.570 --> 00:29:08.530
But if YouTube
had existed then--

00:29:08.530 --> 00:29:11.420
and it came probably
five years afterwards-- I

00:29:11.420 --> 00:29:13.450
wouldn't have bothered
going to TV channels.

00:29:13.450 --> 00:29:16.640
Why would I go to a
TV channel and say,

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:19.530
can I give you 90% of my
earnings to put it out?

00:29:19.530 --> 00:29:21.370
I would have set up
a YouTube channel.

00:29:21.370 --> 00:29:24.110
And if it worked well enough,
worked out some sort of deal--

00:29:24.110 --> 00:29:25.690
I don't know how you pay
them-- but there you go.

00:29:25.690 --> 00:29:27.440
So yeah, I think
YouTube's great for that.

00:29:27.440 --> 00:29:31.150
And weirdly, pranks
and cats seem

00:29:31.150 --> 00:29:33.130
to be the things
that really work.

00:29:33.130 --> 00:29:35.790
And ironically, there is no hub.

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:38.740
If you want humor, you go
to College Humor or UNILAD,

00:29:38.740 --> 00:29:41.240
or I'm sure there's
many cat websites.

00:29:41.240 --> 00:29:43.970
But ironically, there
is no go-to site

00:29:43.970 --> 00:29:47.074
for hidden camera stuff,
which gives me an idea, which

00:29:47.074 --> 00:29:48.240
is what I'm doing right now.

00:29:48.240 --> 00:29:49.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:29:53.557 --> 00:29:55.056
AUDIENCE: Can you
just give us a bit

00:29:55.056 --> 00:29:56.514
of an insight to
your crazy process

00:29:56.514 --> 00:29:59.337
that gave rise to so many of
those pretty exquisite seeds?

00:29:59.337 --> 00:30:00.670
MALE SPEAKER: Well, I will say--

00:30:00.670 --> 00:30:03.265
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] or was
that a collaboration somehow?

00:30:03.265 --> 00:30:04.848
DOM JOLY: I always
say this as a joke,

00:30:04.848 --> 00:30:07.024
but genuinely, it's kind
of probably why I predated

00:30:07.024 --> 00:30:08.940
having walked around
your offices, the concept

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:11.605
of the hot desk and the
sleep pod and stuff.

00:30:11.605 --> 00:30:12.980
When we first
started, because we

00:30:12.980 --> 00:30:16.170
didn't know how to
come up with ideas,

00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:18.749
we'd heard about this thing
called the writing room.

00:30:18.749 --> 00:30:20.165
And we were trying
to be grownups.

00:30:20.165 --> 00:30:21.706
We thought, fuck,
we're on Channel 4.

00:30:21.706 --> 00:30:24.070
So we'd sit in a room
together and literally

00:30:24.070 --> 00:30:26.570
stare at each other, me and
Sam, and have no ideas at all.

00:30:26.570 --> 00:30:27.750
And then we realized
the best way

00:30:27.750 --> 00:30:29.666
to have ideas, especially
for "Trigger Happy,"

00:30:29.666 --> 00:30:32.070
because it was about stuff,
was just to go and do things.

00:30:32.070 --> 00:30:35.339
So I think we blagged--
I think, yeah, Sam and I,

00:30:35.339 --> 00:30:37.130
we went interrailing,
which was just crazy.

00:30:37.130 --> 00:30:39.720
We got Channel 4 to pay for
us to go on a two week railway

00:30:39.720 --> 00:30:41.070
journey around Europe.

00:30:41.070 --> 00:30:42.910
And I think I got
two ideas from that.

00:30:42.910 --> 00:30:44.170
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:45.080 --> 00:30:46.580
We went up to
Scotland to play golf,

00:30:46.580 --> 00:30:48.660
didn't get any ideas from that.

00:30:48.660 --> 00:30:49.640
But we got arrested.

00:30:49.640 --> 00:30:51.574
Because on the way down,
we couldn't resist.

00:30:51.574 --> 00:30:53.490
It's a horrible joke,
and I'm not proud of it.

00:30:53.490 --> 00:30:55.590
But we went through
this tiny little town.

00:30:55.590 --> 00:30:57.570
And there was this sign
outside this building,

00:30:57.570 --> 00:31:00.890
and it said, West Highland's
Dyslexic Association.

00:31:00.890 --> 00:31:03.320
And it was so weird, and
it was like the only thing

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:04.200
in this village.

00:31:04.200 --> 00:31:05.180
And so I'm not proud of this.

00:31:05.180 --> 00:31:05.805
It's not funny.

00:31:05.805 --> 00:31:09.440
But we did instantly get a
little sign, put it on a board,

00:31:09.440 --> 00:31:12.210
and wrote, stop this
now but all misspelled

00:31:12.210 --> 00:31:13.350
and just stood outside it.

00:31:13.350 --> 00:31:14.434
And it just made us laugh.

00:31:14.434 --> 00:31:16.933
And of course they thought we
were having a go at dyslexics,

00:31:16.933 --> 00:31:17.769
which we weren't.

00:31:17.769 --> 00:31:19.810
But to answer your question,
genuinely I normally

00:31:19.810 --> 00:31:22.490
answer this really glibly
and just say, in the pub.

00:31:22.490 --> 00:31:24.279
But genuinely, that
is what happens.

00:31:24.279 --> 00:31:26.820
The only real difference with
something like "Trigger Happy,"

00:31:26.820 --> 00:31:28.290
see everyone goes
out with mates,

00:31:28.290 --> 00:31:29.790
and you get a bit pissed.

00:31:29.790 --> 00:31:31.060
And you all have funny ideas.

00:31:31.060 --> 00:31:33.262
But most of us,
possibly not at Google,

00:31:33.262 --> 00:31:35.095
then wake up the next
morning and think, oh,

00:31:35.095 --> 00:31:37.275
that was a good
night, go to work.

00:31:37.275 --> 00:31:39.092
And I was suddenly
in the stage where

00:31:39.092 --> 00:31:41.050
you'd wake up and think,
fuck, that was a good.

00:31:41.050 --> 00:31:43.710
You'd wait till you were
sober to check it was good.

00:31:43.710 --> 00:31:45.235
And then you'd ring someone up.

00:31:45.235 --> 00:31:46.610
So for instance,
a great example,

00:31:46.610 --> 00:31:48.550
of my favorite sketch
of ever is the snail,

00:31:48.550 --> 00:31:50.930
just because it's kind
of perfect, really.

00:31:50.930 --> 00:31:53.900
And it was this snail coming
up to a zebra crossing,

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:56.982
walking totally normally,
waiting by the zebra crossing.

00:31:56.982 --> 00:31:59.190
Obviously it was some very
sad David Bowie music just

00:31:59.190 --> 00:32:00.390
to make it arty.

00:32:00.390 --> 00:32:01.650
And then everyone stops.

00:32:01.650 --> 00:32:03.940
And then I get on the
floor, and I crawl really

00:32:03.940 --> 00:32:06.320
slowly across the floor.

00:32:06.320 --> 00:32:08.459
And then I get up and
walk across normally.

00:32:08.459 --> 00:32:10.000
Now there's so many
elements to that.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.674
I remember thinking suddenly--
because you get into the mood.

00:32:12.674 --> 00:32:14.590
You see a milkman, you
think, [GASPS] milkman.

00:32:14.590 --> 00:32:15.800
And I suddenly was in
the pub, and I remember.

00:32:15.800 --> 00:32:17.425
It was a Cock &amp; Bottle
in Notting Hill.

00:32:17.425 --> 00:32:19.340
And I go to Sam, I go, snail.

00:32:19.340 --> 00:32:20.210
Snail.

00:32:20.210 --> 00:32:21.500
And the great thing
was we both realized

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:23.410
we're probably in the
only country in the world

00:32:23.410 --> 00:32:24.326
where that would work.

00:32:24.326 --> 00:32:28.906
If I went to a road in America
and started crawling across it

00:32:28.906 --> 00:32:31.610
as a snail, I'd be run
over by a monster truck.

00:32:31.610 --> 00:32:34.409
A redneck would get out and
sort of beat me to death.

00:32:34.409 --> 00:32:35.950
But there is one
bit when you rewatch

00:32:35.950 --> 00:32:39.059
that, if you ever do rewatch it,
I'm going across really slowly.

00:32:39.059 --> 00:32:40.850
And as a cab there and
there's another one.

00:32:40.850 --> 00:32:43.510
And as I'm crawling across,
Sam's hidden in a garden.

00:32:43.510 --> 00:32:46.110
I suddenly realize there's a
gap, obviously, between the two

00:32:46.110 --> 00:32:46.930
cars.

00:32:46.930 --> 00:32:49.190
And if there was a
motorbike coming,

00:32:49.190 --> 00:32:50.870
it wouldn't see the snail.

00:32:50.870 --> 00:32:52.890
And so halfway across
I suddenly think, fuck.

00:32:52.890 --> 00:32:54.330
If I'm in the middle
and a motorbike comes,

00:32:54.330 --> 00:32:55.163
I'm going to be hit.

00:32:55.163 --> 00:32:57.680
So sort of speed up a
bit and then slow down.

00:32:57.680 --> 00:32:59.740
So in hindsight, I've
looked at that sketch.

00:32:59.740 --> 00:33:01.740
And I've thought, if I
was really perfectionist,

00:33:01.740 --> 00:33:04.096
it should have had a tiny
bit of slime coming out

00:33:04.096 --> 00:33:05.210
the back of it.

00:33:05.210 --> 00:33:06.770
But apart from that,
it was perfect.

00:33:06.770 --> 00:33:10.180
And that was a classic example
of how we overplayed it.

00:33:10.180 --> 00:33:13.017
We did it, the first
time, it worked perfectly.

00:33:13.017 --> 00:33:14.850
And literally the first
time we ever did it,

00:33:14.850 --> 00:33:16.891
it was on Red Cliff Gardens,
and that was the one

00:33:16.891 --> 00:33:18.210
we used in "Trigger Happy."

00:33:18.210 --> 00:33:19.280
So we should have
just said, right.

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:19.870
Let's move on.

00:33:19.870 --> 00:33:21.800
But we were so
excited and laughing.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:22.730
Sam goes, do it again.

00:33:22.730 --> 00:33:23.080
Do it again.

00:33:23.080 --> 00:33:24.330
And I go, yeah, all
right, I'll do it again.

00:33:24.330 --> 00:33:25.250
So same thing happens.

00:33:25.250 --> 00:33:27.900
I go up, crawl across, and
suddenly I'm halfway across.

00:33:27.900 --> 00:33:31.280
I've just got past the motorbike
gap, and all I can see is feet.

00:33:31.280 --> 00:33:33.550
And I see that one of
the cars has stopped.

00:33:33.550 --> 00:33:35.910
There's two feet have got
out, like two pairs of feet.

00:33:35.910 --> 00:33:36.740
And they're walking towards me.

00:33:36.740 --> 00:33:37.570
And I was thinking,
fuck, are they

00:33:37.570 --> 00:33:38.420
going to kick me in the face?

00:33:38.420 --> 00:33:40.560
I couldn't move or get
out or anything like that.

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:43.764
And I sort of look up,
and they're two policeman.

00:33:43.764 --> 00:33:45.680
So there's this fantastic
moment which kind of

00:33:45.680 --> 00:33:47.549
reminded me of the
Paul Merton sketch

00:33:47.549 --> 00:33:48.840
where he's a policeman on acid.

00:33:48.840 --> 00:33:52.764
And I can imagine him going,
we observe the gastropod crawl

00:33:52.764 --> 00:33:54.055
slowly across a zebra crossing.

00:33:54.055 --> 00:33:55.870
But anyway, there's
this little standoff.

00:33:55.870 --> 00:33:57.135
And I finally go, all right.

00:33:57.135 --> 00:33:58.874
Like that.

00:33:58.874 --> 00:34:00.290
And there's another
great silence.

00:34:00.290 --> 00:34:02.665
And then a policeman, he's
quite a sweary one, just said,

00:34:02.665 --> 00:34:04.924
I have no fucking idea
what you're fucking doing.

00:34:04.924 --> 00:34:07.340
But if you don't fuck off now,
you'll be fucking arrested.

00:34:07.340 --> 00:34:10.880
So I stand up, and I sprint
off going, sorry about that.

00:34:10.880 --> 00:34:12.650
And we couldn't show
it, because we didn't

00:34:12.650 --> 00:34:15.000
have the policeman's consent.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:18.420
But that's probably my
favorite off out clip.

00:34:18.420 --> 00:34:19.715
But basically the pub, yeah.

00:34:23.810 --> 00:34:26.456
AUDIENCE: Hey, Dom,
thanks for coming in.

00:34:26.456 --> 00:34:27.932
As a cricket fan,
it's a pleasure

00:34:27.932 --> 00:34:30.259
of listening to your interview
on TMS the other day--

00:34:30.259 --> 00:34:31.550
DOM JOLY: "Test Match Special."

00:34:31.550 --> 00:34:32.466
None of you know that.

00:34:32.466 --> 00:34:34.520
That is the highlight
of my entire life.

00:34:34.520 --> 00:34:37.429
I've just had [INAUDIBLE]
said no for the third time.

00:34:37.429 --> 00:34:39.190
This time quite
specifically, I'm

00:34:39.190 --> 00:34:40.500
afraid he's not of our caliber.

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:42.290
You know, yeah, I'm not ready.

00:34:42.290 --> 00:34:43.710
But "Test Match Special."

